        introduction: "Cap Ferret is one of the most emblematic and sought-after destinations on the French Atlantic coast. Located at the tip of the Lege-Cap-Ferret peninsula, this 25 km-long strip of land separates the Atlantic Ocean from the Arcachon Bay. Although Arcachon and Cap Ferret are only a few kilometres apart as the crow flies — separated by the Bay's passes — the road journey requires a full circuit around the Bay, offering an exceptional panorama of this unique European lagoon. Along the route, you will pass through the picturesque oyster-farming ports of Gujan-Mestras, Biganos, Audenge, Lanton and Andernos-les-Bains, where colourful oystermen's huts line the channels. The Ile aux Oiseaux, with its two iconic tchanquees cabins on stilts, is visible from several points along the way. The Cap Ferret peninsula itself is a string of charming villages — L'Herbe, Le Canon, Piraillan, Le Grand Piquey — where life follows the rhythm of the tides and oyster tasting. The Cap Ferret lighthouse, standing 53 metres tall, offers an unrivalled panorama over the Dune du Pilat, the Banc d'Arguin and the Bay entrance.",
        itineraire: "Your driver leaves Arcachon towards La Teste-de-Buch then takes the D1250, a departmental road along the eastern shore of the Arcachon Bay. The route passes through Gujan-Mestras (oyster capital, 7 oyster ports), Le Teich (bird reserve at the Leyre delta), Biganos, Audenge, Lanton and Andernos-les-Bains (France's longest jetty, 232 m). At Ares, the D106 branches towards the Cap Ferret peninsula through pine forest and picturesque villages — Claouey, Le Grand Piquey, Piraillan, Le Canon, L'Herbe — before reaching Cap Ferret itself. Toll-free. Allow 50 min normally, up to 70 min in summer (July-August) when peninsula traffic is heavy.",
        conseils: "The village of L'Herbe, ranked among the Bay's most beautiful oyster villages, deserves a stop for its colourful huts and the Algerian Chapel, a gem of Moorish architecture. Ask your driver to stop at Piraillan or Le Canon harbour to taste oysters directly from the oysterman (€8-12 per dozen). The Cap Ferret lighthouse (€6, 258 steps) offers the Bay's finest panorama with views of the Dune du Pilat and Banc d'Arguin. The Horizon beach on the ocean side is spectacular but currents are strong. The Pointe beach on the Bay side is ideal for families. Alternative: the UBA water shuttle crosses the Bay in 25 min (~€7, pedestrians only), but a taxi is essential to get around the 25 km-long peninsula.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The UBA water shuttle crosses the Bay in 25 min for ~€7 (pedestrians only). But it only serves the Belisaire jetty, and the 25 km peninsula has no practical public transport. The TaxiNeo taxi at €85 — €110 provides complete door-to-door service in 50 min with luggage. For 3-4 passengers, the most comfortable solution.",
